	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>koitsu</b> [ Wed Aug 20, 2014 7:06 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Making top-loader NES as good as AV Famicom?</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Just anecdotal commentary, maybe a bit to make tokumaru feel better too:<br /><br />I own a Famicom AV, a top-loader NES, and a front-loader NES.  I've also owned many original Famicoms over the years.<br /><br />The Famicom AV is the best of the bunch, hands down.  The picture looks wonderful (for composite), and has none of the issues that the top-loader NES has.  I wouldn't mod my Famicom AV if someone paid me to -- it's just fine how it is.  It's what I mainly use for 60-pin carts.<br /><br />My top-loader NES (RF-only of course) has <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?f=9&amp;t=601" class="postlink">the infamous &quot;vertical jailbars&quot; problem</a> and there isn't a single post in that thread that provide a full, definitive explanation for the problem -- or a definitive fix.  All I see in that thread are a lot of people &quot;screwing around&quot; with some success, while others try the same technique and it doesn't work for them.  Because the top-loader NES tends to cost a lot of money, I don't want to mod the thing unless I have an absolute 100% definitive way of fixing the &quot;jailbar&quot; problem.  So this unit mainly sits in storage for me.  The best thing that came with it was the dogbone controller, honestly.  Shame on Nintendo for getting rid of the composite video + RCA audio jacks.  I really do wish I could send the thing back to them and have them replace it with an updated PCB that fixes the jailbars (there are rumours of that floating around the web + this forum, I think).  :/<br /><br />My front-loader NES (using composite) has no visual problems whatsoever, and it's what I mainly use for 72-pin carts.  The only downside is, of course, the shoddy cartridge slot (it has a new contact connector on it, but as has been determined, the replacements are often *too* tight, and result in problems -- I can attest to this fact).

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

